  "prompt": "Dose the inferential statistics examine the relationships between variables? Examine differences between groups or relationships between variables?",
  "response": "Inferential statistics does both:\n\n*   **Examine differences between groups:** Inferential statistics can be used to determine if the differences observed between two or more groups are statistically significant or likely due to chance. For example, comparing the average test scores of students taught using two different methods.\n*   **Examine relationships between variables:** Inferential statistics can also be used to assess the strength and direction of the relationship between two or more variables. For example, determining if there is a correlation between hours studied and exam performance.\n\n**In Summary:** Inferential statistics is a set of methods used to draw conclusions or make generalizations about a population based on data from a sample. It uses sample data to make inferences about the population, and that can involve examining group differences and relationships between variables.",
